The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 The Howrah district court on Friday sentenced eight persons, believed to be CPM supporters, to life imprisonment for their role in the murder of Trinamul activist Gobindo Roy during the 1999 general elections. The eight have also been fined Rs 5,000 each, said public prosecutor Raj Basu.

 Ajmani Khatoon, 6, was mowed down by a Matador near Calcutta National Medical College and Hospital, in Park Circus, on Friday evening. Local residents chased the vehicle and managed to stop it. The driver, Sheikh Kalu, was handed over to police. The girl was taken to hospital, where she was pronounced dead.

 Two women were injured after the owner of an oil mill in Barasat, on the northern fringes of the city, attacked them with a vegetable-knife on Friday morning. Both women were admitted to hospital in a critical condition. Police said trouble was sparked by a dispute between the owners of the oil mill and a shop over the possession of the roof of a building. The women, employed by the shop-owner, were attacked when they were cleaning the roof.

 Anil Das, a professor of the Belghoria-based Animal and Fishery Sciences University, has been missing from his residence since November 19. He left home saying he was accompanying students on an excursion. A complaint has been lodged with Nimta police station. A probe has been ordered.

 An unidentified man, in his thirties, was crushed under the wheels of a minibus on SN Banerjee Road around 8 am on Friday. Police said the victim was crossing the road when the mishap occurred. He was taken to hospital, where he was pronounced dead. The driver fled with his vehicle. 

 A high-level committee of the Travel Agents Federation of India (TAFI) will meet on Saturday to discuss the strategy the group will follow in view of the fare slash by international airlines. Commission for travel agents is on the agenda.

 A computer godown on Garden Reach Road was destroyed in a fire on Friday morning. The fire broke out around 2.40 am. Five fire tenders were pressed into service to bring the blaze under control. Fire brigade officials suspect an electrical short-circuit had caused the blaze. 

 Somesh Goyel has taken over as inspector-general of Border Security Force. He is in charge of the South Bengal frontier. Goyel has replaced Ranjit Kumar Pachnananda, who has taken over as inspector-general (training). Goyel said additional battalions of the force would be deployed on the South Bengal frontier to check infiltration. The fencing of the border will be completed soon.

 The feud within the North 24-Parganas unit of the Congress intensified on Friday, with senior leaders Abdul Gaffar Khan and Debi Ghosal refusing to join the party?s ?law-violation? programme scheduled for Saturday. District leader Ashutosh Laha is organising the agitation. 

